<script>
  window.onload = function(){
    var universe = new Universe({ sun:{},earth:{type:'center'},moon:{} });
    universe.label  = true;

    universe.satellitePaths    = true;
    universe.includeSatellites = true;

    universe.rate = .15;
    universe.min_planet_size = 5;
    universe.max_planet_size = 5;

    universe.planets.sun.cycles([
      {radius:'1.25*60;0',mm:'0;59,8,20'}, // shatir's mean sun
    ]) ;
    universe.planets.sun.name = 'mean sun';
    // http://www2.kenyon.edu/Depts/Math/Aydin/Teach/Sp11/191/PreCopernican.pdf
    universe.planets.moon.cycles([
      {mm:"13;13,45,39,40", radius:"60"},
      {mm:"-13;3,53,46,18",radius:"6;35"},
      {mm:"24;22,53,23",radius:"1;25"},
    ]);

    universe.setup(); 
  }
</script>

<div id='lefttext'>
  Ibn al-Shatir's lunar model, identical in all respects but some parameters to Copernicus',
  as described in <%= link_to "Victor Roberts' 1957 paper", "http://www2.kenyon.edu/Depts/Math/Aydin/Teach/Sp11/191/PreCopernican.pdf" %>.  God knows better.


</div>

<div id='righttext'>
  It notably predicts far less variation in the size of the lunar disc than <%= link_to "the earlier Greek models", "/ptolemy/moon" %>.  Roughly speaking the first epicycle, slowly
  changing the mean Earth-Moon distance, accounts for
  <%= link_to "evection", "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Evection" %>, while the second smaller
  epicycle accounts for
  <%= link_to "the equation of center", "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equation_of_the_center" %>.
 
</div>

